00:10:04,276 --> 00:10:05,350
<i>but, instead,</i>

233
00:10:05,605 --> 00:10:07,353
<i>what he told
was the truth.</i>

234
00:10:07,608 --> 00:10:09,310
- Me.
- What?

235
00:10:10,567 --> 00:10:12,362
You killed someone?

236
00:10:15,568 --> 00:10:16,660
Who did you kill?

237
00:10:16,697 --> 00:10:19,243
- I didn't.
- You didn't-- that's why somebody died.

238
00:10:19,285 --> 00:10:20,451
Please stop talking.

239
00:10:20,708 --> 00:10:22,373
- You didn't what?
- Looky here,

240
00:10:22,585 --> 00:10:24,300
you need a ticket
to ride this ride.

241
00:10:24,338 --> 00:10:25,550
If your ticket gets punched,

242
00:10:25,585 --> 00:10:27,470
then you got to take
somebody else's ticket.

243
00:10:27,505 --> 00:10:29,342
- Why are you still talking?
- I'm ripping off the band-aid.

244
00:10:29,377 --> 00:10:31,050
I'm not a ripper--
I pull up a corner a little at a time,

245
00:10:31,087 --> 00:10:33,182
then I run it under warm water,
and I pull it up a little more.

246
00:10:33,216 --> 00:10:34,712
- It's a process.
- Let it rip.

247
00:10:35,218 --> 00:10:37,440
I didn't actively kill.
I'm not an active killer.

248
00:10:37,477 --> 00:10:38,883
I'm not a killer.

249
00:10:39,685 --> 00:10:42,640
- You killed someone for me?
- It wasn't my fault.

250
00:10:42,898 --> 00:10:44,390
It's a random proximity thing.

251
00:10:44,606 --> 00:10:47,102
There was no choice or
decision-making whatsoever.

252
00:10:47,275 --> 00:10:49,943
- It just happened.
- But you knew it would happen.

253
00:10:50,156 --> 00:10:52,603
I was incapacitated with
not being able to think.

254
00:10:52,815 --> 00:10:54,790
I had one thought in my head,
and it was of you,

255
00:10:54,825 --> 00:10:56,962
and it clogged me up so no other
thoughts could get through,

256
00:10:56,998 --> 00:10:58,623
including the one telling
me to touch you again.

257
00:10:58,655 --> 00:11:00,080
So every minute I've
been celebrating

258
00:11:00,115 --> 00:11:01,953
wasn't really mine
to celebrate.

259
00:11:02,536 --> 00:11:05,080
<i>As Chuck considered the
life she was living</i>

260
00:11:05,296 --> 00:11:06,791
<i>that was not her own...</i>

261
00:11:07,295 --> 00:11:10,080
<i>...Olive considered the
life she was not living.</i>

262
00:11:10,296 --> 00:11:11,690
Might I make an observation?

263
00:11:11,886 --> 00:11:14,430
- Compliment or criticism?
- A neutral thought, I would say.

264
00:11:14,467 --> 00:11:16,461
It's neither complimentary
nor critical.

265
00:11:16,768 --> 00:11:19,301
Neutral thought gives me pause.

266
00:11:19,517 --> 00:11:22,012
Neutral for only this
portion of the conversation,

267
00:11:22,016 --> 00:11:23,900
but I do have
complimentary observations

268
00:11:23,936 --> 00:11:26,320
as part of a follow-up discussion,
which I intend

269
00:11:26,357 --> 00:11:28,452
to headline with an offer to
repair your espresso machine.

270
00:11:28,485 --> 00:11:30,571
- What's your neutral thought?
- You deem decidedly unhappy.

271
00:11:30,607 --> 00:11:33,102
- I haven't decided that.
- No anxieties, neuroses,

272
00:11:33,196 --> 00:11:34,822
- pathologies?
- Garden variety.

273
00:11:35,156 --> 00:11:37,452
- What are you beating at?
- I'm beating at happiness.

274
00:11:37,488 --> 00:11:39,073
I've beaten it into submission

275
00:11:39,408 --> 00:11:41,152
and bottled it for convenience.

276
00:11:44,707 --> 00:11:46,162
It's homeopathic.

277
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:48,493
Meaning it deeply
relates to gay people.

278
00:11:48,548 --> 00:11:50,790
"Gay" only in that they
are bright and happy.

279
00:11:50,875 --> 00:11:53,351
You never have to worry about the
oxygen leaving the room again.

280
00:11:53,387 --> 00:11:55,541
Don't go bothering the
customers with this.

281
00:11:55,847 --> 00:11:58,510
This is a pie house,
not some herbal crack den.

282
00:12:01,098 --> 00:12:02,842
Chuck, say something.

283
00:12:02,896 --> 00:12:04,862
I can't, for the life of me,
think of anything to say.

284
00:12:04,897 --> 00:12:07,090
Oh, I forgot--
it's not even my life, is it?

285
00:12:19,535 --> 00:12:20,782
Not now.

286
00:12:23,576 --> 00:12:24,953
I feel violated.

287
00:12:25,328 --> 00:12:26,660
That was my information.

288
00:12:26,918 --> 00:12:29,212
There's your information,
and then there's my information.

289
00:12:29,248 --> 00:12:30,542
That was our information.

290
00:12:30,576 --> 00:12:33,573
You let a man die on our time,
a man who could have been me.

291
00:12:33,716 --> 00:12:35,262
- It wasn't.
- But it could have been.

292
00:12:35,297 --> 00:12:36,681
That was a business
associate of mine.

293
00:12:36,717 --> 00:12:38,683
Who do you think hooked
us up with corpse bride?

294
00:12:38,718 --> 00:12:40,462
But he stole stuff
off dead people.

295
00:12:40,467 --> 00:12:42,230
Regardless of how he
ran his own business,

296
00:12:42,266 --> 00:12:43,773
he never interfered
with how I ran mine.

297
00:12:43,807 --> 00:12:45,812
You, on the other hand,
made me an accomplice to a murder.

298
00:12:45,848 --> 00:12:47,611
Stop saying that.
I didn't murder anyone.

299
00:12:47,706 --> 00:12:48,901
There was no malice
or forethought.

300
00:12:48,938 --> 00:12:50,060
Okay, maybe

301
00:12:50,316 --> 00:12:52,182
accidental,
involuntary manslaughter.

302
00:12:52,737 --> 00:12:56,810
Oh, you accidentally,
involuntarily let dead girl live?

303
00:12:58,157 --> 00:13:00,231
That's what I thought
you was gonna say.

304
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:02,070
Lawrence Schatz was murdered
enough for his brother

305
00:13:02,106 --> 00:13:04,153
to hire me to find
out who killed him.

306
00:13:04,708 --> 00:13:07,950
- Why did you take this case?
- You want me to take this case.

307
00:13:08,205 --> 00:13:10,453
I'm making sure nobody
else solves it.

308
00:13:10,747 --> 00:13:13,240
Look, I didn't want to go
down this road with you.

309
00:13:13,298 --> 00:13:14,591
I'm sensitive to
your experience.

310
00:13:14,627 --> 00:13:15,980
I understand that
it's traumatic.

311
00:13:16,015 --> 00:13:17,973
But now I need to chat
with Lawrence Schatz

312
00:13:18,007 --> 00:13:20,252
before he goes into
the ground tomorrow.

313
00:13:20,427 --> 00:13:21,931
I'm not going back to
that funeral home.

314
00:13:21,967 --> 00:13:24,142
It's returning to the scene of a crime--
that's just sloppy.

315
00:13:24,177 --> 00:13:25,773
And by the way,
to ask him what?

316
00:13:25,845 --> 00:13:27,222
I want to ask
Lawrence what he did

317
00:13:27,258 --> 00:13:29,150
with all those precious
family heirlooms.

318
00:13:29,187 --> 00:13:30,602
So you can...

319
00:13:31,017 --> 00:13:35,023
return it to the families
and help heal the grieving?

320
00:13:35,358 --> 00:13:39,153
Yeah, 'cause after the grieving stops,
you have Joy,

321
00:13:39,368 --> 00:13:40,733
and with Joy comes money,

322
00:13:40,947 --> 00:13:44,490
and Louis Schatz will stop asking
questions about how his brother died.

323
00:13:46,078 --> 00:13:49,240
I'm not touching Lawrence Schatz.
It's too traumatic.

324
00:13:49,496 --> 00:13:51,622
I am fragile on this issue.

325
00:13:51,917 --> 00:13:53,622
- That how it is?
- Yeah.

326
00:13:53,958 --> 00:13:55,293
That's how it is.

327
00:13:55,586 --> 00:13:58,792
Whatever you say... killer.

328
00:13:59,846 --> 00:14:02,631
<i>The pie maker
rationalized circumstances</i>

329
00:14:02,668 --> 00:14:06,223
<i>beyond his control were responsible
for Lawrence Schatz's death.</i>

330
00:14:06,438 --> 00:14:07,842
<i>He was not to blame.</i>

331
00:14:08,265 --> 00:14:10,512
<i>Rationalizing those
rationalizations</i>

332
00:14:10,895 --> 00:14:12,943
<i>to the man he
inadvertently killed</i>

333
00:14:13,066 --> 00:14:14,863
<i>was something he'd
rather not do.</i>

334
00:14:14,898 --> 00:14:16,443
I want to talk to Louis Schatz.

335
00:14:17,105 --> 00:14:19,193
I want you to talk to him, too.

336
00:14:21,446 --> 00:14:23,361
Why would I do that?

337
00:14:23,438 --> 00:14:25,903
So you can apologize,
and I can say "thank you."

338
00:14:29,665 --> 00:14:33,410
<i>As the pie maker found himself
back at the scene of his crime,</i>

339
00:14:33,467 --> 00:14:36,873
<i>Chuck found herself back
where her second life began,</i>

340
00:14:37,085 --> 00:14:40,581
<i>now with the understanding
of how it began.</i>

341
00:14:44,805 --> 00:14:46,300
Have you already been here?

342
00:14:48,475 --> 00:14:50,840
- Lawrence Schatz?
- Louis.

343
00:14:50,855 --> 00:14:52,050
Lawrence is dead.

344
00:14:52,358 --> 00:14:53,761
- Hey, Emerson.
- Hey, Louie.

345
00:14:54,018 --> 00:14:55,810
"Darling Mermaid Darlings."

346
00:14:56,027 --> 00:14:57,570
Yeah, we just
buried their niece,

347
00:14:57,608 --> 00:14:59,203
lonely tourist
Charlotte Charles.

348
00:14:59,235 --> 00:15:01,412
- You see they're on tour.
- I do. It's so exciting.

349
00:15:01,446 --> 00:15:03,590
Tour was canceled.
They're in a dark place,

350
00:15:03,775 --> 00:15:06,411
some kind of an emotional relapse.
Have we met before?

351
00:15:06,448 --> 00:15:07,740
- No.
- No.

352
00:15:08,116 --> 00:15:10,131
<i>The cause of the Darling
Mermaid Darlings'</i>

353
00:15:10,166 --> 00:15:12,032
<i>emotional relapse
was this...</i>

354
00:15:13,667 --> 00:15:15,291
<i>After losing Chuck,</i>

355
00:15:15,547 --> 00:15:18,182
<i>aunts Lily and Vivian had
a better appreciation</i>

356
00:15:18,217 --> 00:15:19,960
<i>of the preciousness
of life.</i>

357
00:15:20,178 --> 00:15:22,302
<i>With luggage packed,
bonnets cinched,</i>

358
00:15:22,335 --> 00:15:24,331
<i>and sunscreen
vigorously applied,</i>

359
00:15:24,557 --> 00:15:26,503
<i>they were ready
at last to start</i>

360
00:15:26,596 --> 00:15:28,801
<i>their long-awaited
comeback tour,</i>

361
00:15:29,016 --> 00:15:31,262
<i>but not today.
To their surprise,</i>

362
00:15:31,555 --> 00:15:33,650
<i>there was something waiting
in the morning mail,</i>

363
00:15:33,687 --> 00:15:36,471
<i>alongside the thrifty
nickel and the pennysaver.</i>

364
00:15:36,685 --> 00:15:38,062
It's from Charlotte.

365
00:15:38,315 --> 00:15:39,641
<i>In that moment,</i>

366
00:15:39,855 --> 00:15:41,313
<i>only for a moment,</i>

367
00:15:41,607 --> 00:15:43,690
<i>aunt Lily forgot
Chuck was dead...</i>

368
00:15:44,027 --> 00:15:45,942
<i>or, at least,
dead to her.</i>

369
00:15:46,157 --> 00:15:47,570
<i>Then she remembered.</i>

370
00:15:52,287 --> 00:15:54,410
Poor, poor Charlotte.

371
00:15:55,535 --> 00:15:57,081
<i>And with that,</i>

372
00:15:57,306 --> 00:15:59,041
<i>the Darling
Mermaid Darlings</i>

373
00:15:59,166 --> 00:16:01,042
<i>cancelled their
comeback tour.</i>

374
00:16:01,428 --> 00:16:03,322
I'm having a martini
and going to bed.

375
00:16:06,637 --> 00:16:08,053
You know, uh, Larry died

376
00:16:08,307 --> 00:16:10,692
on the same day we buried lonely
tourist Charlotte Charles.

377
00:16:10,728 --> 00:16:13,593
- We don't often bury a celebrity.
- Celebrity.

378
00:16:13,936 --> 00:16:16,022
Burying a celebrity,
even a pseudo-celebrity,

379
00:16:16,057 --> 00:16:17,610
who's only famous
for how she died,

380
00:16:17,646 --> 00:16:19,441
must be a coup for any funeral home,
I'd imagine.

381
00:16:19,478 --> 00:16:20,601
It would be,

382
00:16:20,896 --> 00:16:23,193
if it wasn't for Larry's
grave-robbing scandal

383
00:16:23,315 --> 00:16:24,482
or his murder.

384
00:16:25,155 --> 00:16:26,482
He's in here.

385
00:16:27,076 --> 00:16:30,111
I got it locked,
so no one can defile his dead body.

386
00:16:30,327 --> 00:16:31,772
Are you sure he was murdered?

387
00:16:31,997 --> 00:16:33,693
I've been putting
it all together.

388
00:16:33,788 --> 00:16:36,783
And, boy,
do I have a tale to tell.

389
00:16:37,125 --> 00:16:39,420
<i>And this is the tale
Louis Schatz told.</i>

390
00:16:39,757 --> 00:16:42,150
<i>He detailed a series
of events that began</i>

391
00:16:42,255 --> 00:16:44,921
<i>when he caught
his brother ***</i>

392
00:16:45,176 --> 00:16:47,013
I was just prepping
the body for burial.

393
00:16:47,048 --> 00:16:48,920
Your wife's gorgeous.
How'd you meet?

394
00:16:49,215 --> 00:16:51,222
Aw, Larry. How could you?

395
00:16:51,518 --> 00:16:53,961
<i>When word of Lawrence's
grave-robbing ways</i>

396
00:16:54,138 --> 00:16:56,653
<i>spread through the sleepy
hollow of Coeur d'Coeurs,</i>

397
00:16:56,686 --> 00:16:58,313
<i>there was
public outrage.</i>

398
00:16:58,605 --> 00:17:01,521
<i>Bulk hate mail and death
threats by the hundreds</i>

399
00:17:01,535 --> 00:17:03,733
<i>frightened the truth
out of Lawrence.</i>

400
00:17:03,896 --> 00:17:05,191
<i>According to Louis,</i>

401
00:17:05,238 --> 00:17:06,880
<i>he only confessed
his sins</i>

402
00:17:06,945 --> 00:17:09,372
<i>to the one person he
knew would forgive him.</i>

403
00:17:09,406 --> 00:17:12,242
I buried it all where
no one could find it.

404
00:17:12,447 --> 00:17:14,090
You have to give
everything back.

405
00:17:14,205 --> 00:17:15,861
But I buried it really deep.

406
00:17:16,116 --> 00:17:19,260
<i>Louis insisted what his brother
Lawrence did not confess</i>

407
00:17:19,285 --> 00:17:23,003
<i>was where he had hidden the
spoils of his grave-robbery.</i>

408
00:17:23,795 --> 00:17:26,333
<i>That secret he took
to his own grave</i>

409
00:17:26,637 --> 00:17:29,130
<i>when he presumably died
of heart failure.</i>

410
00:17:29,426 --> 00:17:31,921
<i>But as Louis was besieged
by angry families</i>

411
00:17:32,138 --> 00:17:34,310
<i>seeking the return of
stolen heirlooms,</i>

412
00:17:34,346 --> 00:17:35,840
<i>he began to wonder--</i>

413
00:17:36,135 --> 00:17:38,141
<i>What if it wasn't
heart failure?</i>

414
00:17:38,397 --> 00:17:40,432
<i>What if his brother
was murdered?</i>

415
00:17:40,645 --> 00:17:43,783
<i>What if, in the hundreds of letters
addressed to Lawrence Schatz,</i>

416
00:17:43,818 --> 00:17:46,813
<i>threatening his life,
one of them was a promise?</i>

417
00:17:48,485 --> 00:17:50,480
<i>What if his brother
was murdered,</i>

418
00:17:50,775 --> 00:17:52,900
<i>and what if his
murder was next?</i>

419
00:17:53,115 --> 00:17:54,783
I told Larry it was bad karma.

420
00:17:54,997 --> 00:17:57,091
The whole thing makes me sick--
just sick.

421
00:17:57,116 --> 00:17:58,842
Do you know what it's like
to live in daily fear

422
00:17:58,875 --> 00:18:00,420
that one minute
you could drop dead

423
00:18:00,456 --> 00:18:03,802
right where you're standing because
of something somebody else did?

424
00:18:03,835 --> 00:18:06,210
I feel like I could
smoke a cigar with you.

425
00:18:06,425 --> 00:18:08,083
I don't smoke. That was Larry.

426
00:18:08,546 --> 00:18:11,300
Here. Take it. He would.

427
00:18:12,927 --> 00:18:14,883
It's true what they
say about twins--

428
00:18:15,175 --> 00:18:17,691
His life was my life.
It's strange to share someone's life.

429
00:18:17,726 --> 00:18:19,510
I feel like mine's tainted now.

430
00:18:19,726 --> 00:18:21,671
I would love to give
back what he took.

431
00:18:21,897 --> 00:18:23,572
Can we have a moment
to pay our respects,

432
00:18:23,607 --> 00:18:26,103
while you go rustle up
that hate mail to go?

433
00:18:29,777 --> 00:18:30,863
Yeah.

434
00:18:35,285 --> 00:18:38,743
<i>As they stood over the man
who died for one of them</i>

435
00:18:38,807 --> 00:18:40,552
<i>and was killed
by the other,</i>

436
00:18:40,787 --> 00:18:42,283
<i>Chuck and the pie maker</i>

437
00:18:42,456 --> 00:18:44,300
<i>carefully planned
their words.</i>

438
00:18:47,877 --> 00:18:49,843
- Yes?
- I'm sorry for what I did.

439
00:18:49,908 --> 00:18:52,750
It was mostly an accident,
but partially on purpose.

440
00:18:53,005 --> 00:18:55,052
However inadvertent,
I am sorry I did it.

441
00:18:56,317 --> 00:18:57,513
That's all.

442
00:18:59,556 --> 00:19:00,763
Hello.

443
00:19:01,146 --> 00:19:03,140
Lonely tourist
Charlotte Charles,

444
00:19:03,438 --> 00:19:05,281
are you part of my
welcoming committee?

445
00:19:05,318 --> 00:19:07,321
More like a beneficiary,
in that I'm still alive,

446
00:19:07,358 --> 00:19:09,900
- which is why you're not.
- Am I a human sacrifice?

447
00:19:10,108 --> 00:19:11,941
- Hey, Emerson.
- Oh, hey, Larry.

448
00:19:12,237 --> 00:19:14,702
What'd you do with all that stuff
you stole off them dead people?

449
00:19:14,736 --> 00:19:16,461
Why don't you ask Louis
what he did with it?

450
00:19:16,498 --> 00:19:18,120
- Louis said you buried it.
- And you believed him.

451
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:19,951
You met Louis?
Hey, how did I die?

452
00:19:20,208 --> 00:19:22,092
Did somebody kill me?
Hey, did Louis kill me?

453
00:19:22,126 --> 00:19:24,420
- Nobody killed you, per se.
- Y-yes, they did.

454
00:19:24,548 --> 00:19:25,940
It was so that I could live.

455
00:19:25,997 --> 00:19:27,552
It wasn't personal.
I didn't pick you.

456
00:19:27,585 --> 00:19:28,933
The selection is purely random,

457
00:19:28,967 --> 00:19:30,761
but it didn't help that
you were in the next room.

458
00:19:30,798 --> 00:19:32,301
Louis has all that
stuff you stole?

459
00:19:32,335 --> 00:19:34,131
We stole--
it was a family business.

460
00:19:34,345 --> 00:19:36,060
Louis has everything
but this watch.

461
00:19:36,095 --> 00:19:37,891
My dad gave me a
watch just like that.

462
00:19:37,925 --> 00:19:40,441
You were buried with it.
Well, you were supposed to be.

463
00:19:40,478 --> 00:19:41,870
Caught me in the cookie jar.

464
00:19:42,266 --> 00:19:44,102
You stole that
off my dead body?

465
00:19:44,358 --> 00:19:46,603
Your dead body wasn't
doing anything with it.

466
00:19:46,857 --> 00:19:48,272
Hey, what are you doing?

467
00:19:50,856 --> 00:19:52,060
It's stuck.

468
00:19:52,445 --> 00:19:54,861
- You better be playing.
