471
00:20:08,966 --> 00:20:11,171
<i>Random selection
was about to begin.</i>

472
00:20:11,375 --> 00:20:12,752
5 seconds!

473
00:20:13,086 --> 00:20:15,180
Maybe I should let him
have his life back.

474
00:20:16,347 --> 00:20:17,800
Not how it works.

475
00:20:18,097 --> 00:20:20,250
No regifting!

476
00:20:21,438 --> 00:20:22,890
That wasn't cool, you guys.

477
00:20:32,565 --> 00:20:33,650
Look.

478
00:20:34,987 --> 00:20:37,982
Aw, that was so sweet of my
aunts to bury it with me.

479
00:20:39,286 --> 00:20:41,570
My dad had it,
and then I had it.

480
00:20:41,865 --> 00:20:44,321
Then I suppose he had it,
which really steams me.

481
00:20:44,705 --> 00:20:46,781
- You got it back?
- Yeah, I did.

482
00:20:48,495 --> 00:20:50,293
It's nice to get things back.

483
00:20:52,007 --> 00:20:54,581
My aunts cancelled their tour.

484
00:20:55,967 --> 00:20:58,550
I was really looking forward
to hiding out in the crowd

485
00:20:58,586 --> 00:21:00,651
with a big pair of
sunglasses and a parasol,

486
00:21:00,687 --> 00:21:02,931
watching them perform
in their mermaid suits.

487
00:21:05,645 --> 00:21:07,511
He said they were
in a dark place.

488
00:21:07,765 --> 00:21:10,161
He said they had some kind
of emotional relapse.

489
00:21:11,145 --> 00:21:14,351
- Couldn't we just...
- You can't see your aunts.

490
00:21:15,946 --> 00:21:17,273
I'm sorry.

491
00:21:24,665 --> 00:21:27,701
<i>If Chuck could not regift
the life she'd been given,</i>

492
00:21:27,796 --> 00:21:29,851
<i>she at least wanted to
find a way to share it</i>

493
00:21:29,886 --> 00:21:32,250
<i>with her aunts
Lily and Vivian.</i>

494
00:21:37,967 --> 00:21:40,173
Anybody dead back there
that shouldn't be?

495
00:21:40,428 --> 00:21:41,422
No.

496
00:21:41,965 --> 00:21:43,133
Sweet.

497
00:21:44,307 --> 00:21:47,553
<i>After Lawrence Schatz was
exposed as a grave robber,</i>

498
00:21:47,808 --> 00:21:50,020
<i>the mailbox at the Schatz
brothers funeral home</i>

499
00:21:50,058 --> 00:21:54,020
<i>received 1,867
hate letters,</i>

500
00:21:54,118 --> 00:21:57,733
<i>each one a catalog of heirlooms
feared stolen or lost.</i>

501
00:21:57,947 --> 00:21:59,730
Louis Schatz is a big,
fat liar.

502
00:21:59,778 --> 00:22:02,321
And I say "fat" in reference
to his size as a liar,

503
00:22:02,406 --> 00:22:04,250
not as a judgment of
his physical appearance.

504
00:22:04,285 --> 00:22:05,731
I'm not mad at him for lying.

505
00:22:05,955 --> 00:22:08,490
If I could pin my crimes
on some dead relative,

506
00:22:08,505 --> 00:22:11,700
especially some guilty dead relative,
I'd certainly consider it.

507
00:22:11,798 --> 00:22:14,041
That sucker played me
like boo-boo the fool--

508
00:22:14,087 --> 00:22:15,882
Hiring me to make
him look innocent.

509
00:22:16,008 --> 00:22:18,683
He knew all along where that
dead-people treasure was buried.

510
00:22:18,715 --> 00:22:19,861
It's all right, though.

511
00:22:20,007 --> 00:22:23,060
I'm gonna follow his lying fat
ass until he lead me right to it.

512
00:22:23,095 --> 00:22:24,343
Then I'm gonna take it.

513
00:22:24,636 --> 00:22:27,603
- You can't steal dead people's stuff.
- I'm not the one who stole it.

514
00:22:27,636 --> 00:22:30,641
I don't condone what they did,
but it's once removed now.

515
00:22:30,897 --> 00:22:33,113
I'm not the pirate--
I'm just looking for treasure.

516
00:22:33,145 --> 00:22:35,430
- The pirate metaphore is weak.
- It's apt.

517
00:22:35,738 --> 00:22:37,823
I find a dead pirate treasure
at the bottom of the sea,

518
00:22:37,858 --> 00:22:39,490
I take it--
doesn't matter whose it was,

519
00:22:39,526 --> 00:22:41,790
if whose it was is dead,
'cause it's mine now.

520
00:22:41,826 --> 00:22:43,280
This-- this isn't a doubloon.

521
00:22:43,488 --> 00:22:44,932
This is somebody's something.

522
00:22:45,116 --> 00:22:47,370
Stealing from a pirate who
already stole is still stealing.

523
00:22:47,405 --> 00:22:48,662
It's not once removed.

524
00:22:48,868 --> 00:22:50,421
Somebody didn't
want that something

525
00:22:50,455 --> 00:22:52,540
if they buried it with
somebody who can't use it.

526
00:22:52,578 --> 00:22:54,923
What if Lawrence Schatz was
murdered for this buried treasure?

527
00:22:54,957 --> 00:22:57,001
Well, was gonna be
before you got to him.

528
00:22:57,046 --> 00:22:58,513
Why'd you have to
say it like that?

529
00:22:58,546 --> 00:23:00,390
There's a lot of hostility
in these letters.

530
00:23:00,428 --> 00:23:03,351
Do you realize how angry someone
has to be to put pen to paper?

531
00:23:03,387 --> 00:23:04,931
I mean,
these people are furious.

532
00:23:04,965 --> 00:23:06,522
Any one of them
could be the killer.

533
00:23:06,555 --> 00:23:08,222
Lawrence Schatz
wasn't murdered.

534
00:23:08,476 --> 00:23:12,141
He was accidentally,
involuntarily manslaughtered.

535
00:23:12,397 --> 00:23:14,592
- I appreciate that.
- There ain't no killer.

536
00:23:17,606 --> 00:23:19,271
<i>***</i>

537
00:23:19,367 --> 00:23:21,902
<i>murder was on
someone's mind.</i>

538
00:23:26,785 --> 00:23:29,382
<i>As Chuck catalogued
another missing heirloom,</i>

539
00:23:29,406 --> 00:23:31,701
<i>she considered what
her aunts had lost</i>

540
00:23:31,958 --> 00:23:34,052
<i>and how it could
never be returned.</i>

541
00:23:34,286 --> 00:23:35,662
This is depressing.

542
00:23:40,336 --> 00:23:41,792
Did you say "depressing"?

543
00:23:47,177 --> 00:23:50,302
FDA-approved
pharmaceutical-grade herbology.

544
00:23:50,597 --> 00:23:52,142
Like a bully for your emotions.

545
00:23:52,226 --> 00:23:54,530
Emotions need to be bullied,
or at least groomed.

546
00:23:54,568 --> 00:23:57,443
Indulging depression is like
indulging a horrible, willful child.

547
00:23:57,476 --> 00:23:58,691
If you allow it
to run roughshod,

548
00:23:58,727 --> 00:24:00,992
you'll find yourself
catering to its every whim.

549
00:24:01,025 --> 00:24:02,490
So, bully it,
and bully it good.

550
00:24:02,527 --> 00:24:04,371
Everyone needs to be
bullied sometimes.

551
00:24:04,408 --> 00:24:05,750
Do you have any literature?

552
00:24:05,945 --> 00:24:08,000
I have a pamphlet,
if you'd like to read that.

553
00:24:08,037 --> 00:24:09,922
Our herbs for depression
contain proven ingredients

554
00:24:09,957 --> 00:24:12,550
in the proper doses,
manufactured with the strictest

555
00:24:12,618 --> 00:24:14,873
- of quality control.
- "Herbs for depression" sounds

556
00:24:14,905 --> 00:24:17,562
- so much more civil than "antidepressants."
- And with fewer side effects.

557
00:24:17,595 --> 00:24:19,550
- Can I have these?
- I can't just give it to you.

558
00:24:19,585 --> 00:24:20,980
It's a controlled substance.

559
00:24:22,086 --> 00:24:23,540
But I have a sample pack.

560
00:24:26,385 --> 00:24:28,553
<i>Chuck wasn't thinking
of herself.</i>

561
00:24:28,886 --> 00:24:30,730
<i>She was thinking
of her aunts.</i>

562
00:24:32,595 --> 00:24:35,472
<i>Though her life she was
living was not her own</i>

563
00:24:35,685 --> 00:24:37,881
<i>Chuck found a way
for her living gift</i>

564
00:24:37,977 --> 00:24:40,351
<i>to be the gift
that kept giving.</i>

565
00:24:40,816 --> 00:24:44,693
<i>She took responsibility for
Lily and Vivian's happiness.</i>

566
00:24:44,867 --> 00:24:46,152
<i>And took action.</i>

567
00:25:01,546 --> 00:25:03,830
<i>Even after she was
dead and gone,</i>

568
00:25:04,015 --> 00:25:07,160
<i>Chuck found a way to do what
she had done all her life--</i>

569
00:25:07,345 --> 00:25:09,092
<i>Care for her aunts.</i>

570
00:25:12,518 --> 00:25:15,222
- Oh, you forgot one.
- Outside my zone.

571
00:25:15,435 --> 00:25:16,931
Oh, it's not so far.

572
00:25:17,228 --> 00:25:19,771
Do you want to be a delivery
boy or a delivery man?

573
00:25:19,815 --> 00:25:21,433
Boy. You be a man.

574
00:25:22,437 --> 00:25:23,892
But it's my day off.

575
00:25:24,355 --> 00:25:25,811
And I'm a girl!

576
00:25:26,155 --> 00:25:27,360
<i>In her own way,</i>

577
00:25:27,696 --> 00:25:30,780
<i>Olive identified with the
plight of the abandoned pie.</i>

578
00:25:31,076 --> 00:25:33,843
<i>It was meant for someone,
and without a little effort,</i>

579
00:25:33,875 --> 00:25:37,160
<i>it would never be with the
one it was meant to be with.</i>

580
00:25:38,497 --> 00:25:40,581
<i>And tragically
for Louis Schatz,</i>

581
00:25:40,876 --> 00:25:43,413
<i>he was meant to be
with his brother.</i>

582
00:25:53,926 --> 00:25:56,021
Hey, I didn't hear you
leave this morning.

583
00:25:56,267 --> 00:25:58,112
I didn't hear you
come in last night.

584
00:25:58,357 --> 00:26:00,473
I was having
conversations with myself.

585
00:26:00,686 --> 00:26:02,132
What did you guys talk about?

586
00:26:02,398 --> 00:26:04,593
I asked myself,
"if I were storming a castle

587
00:26:04,605 --> 00:26:06,911
to save a Sleeping Beauty
from the jaws of death,

588
00:26:06,946 --> 00:26:09,621
and in the melee,
my sword of truth flew swift and sure

589
00:26:09,655 --> 00:26:11,292
and killed an unfortunate
outlaw huddled nearby,

590
00:26:11,326 --> 00:26:12,990
how would I feel?"

591
00:26:13,327 --> 00:26:15,332
Did you successfully
rescue Sleeping Beauty?

592
00:26:15,367 --> 00:26:16,530
In this scenario, yeah.

593
00:26:16,865 --> 00:26:18,812
And how would you
feel, hypothetically?

594
00:26:18,825 --> 00:26:20,970
I'd feel happy and then bad,
and primarily happy,

595
00:26:21,006 --> 00:26:23,043
and then I'd think
about it too much,

596
00:26:23,255 --> 00:26:24,651
and then I'd feel bad again.

597
00:26:24,915 --> 00:26:27,290
That's kind of how I
feel/exactly how I feel.

598
00:26:30,136 --> 00:26:32,501
Well, I don't want you
to think I'm a killer.

599
00:26:32,967 --> 00:26:34,812
I don't want to think
you're a killer, either.

600
00:26:34,848 --> 00:26:36,942
I want to think of you
as Prince Charming.

601
00:26:37,387 --> 00:26:39,922
I'm not setting a standard
for you to live up to.

602
00:26:39,938 --> 00:26:41,970
- It's just--
- That's not good.

603
00:26:46,358 --> 00:26:50,482
- Did you-- did you--
- No. No!

604
00:26:50,777 --> 00:26:52,623
<i>As Chuck and the pie
maker considered</i>

605
00:26:52,658 --> 00:26:54,951
<i>the dead Schatz brother
in the freezer,</i>

606
00:26:55,327 --> 00:26:58,100
<i>Olive snook considered
the consequences</i>

607
00:26:58,116 --> 00:26:59,951
<i>of driving several
towns away</i>

608
00:27:00,247 --> 00:27:01,750
<i>to make a delivery
to an address</i>

609
00:27:01,786 --> 00:27:04,790
<i>that was not part of the
regular delivery route.</i>

610
00:27:26,996 --> 00:27:29,482
<i>As she drew closer
to the front door,</i>

611
00:27:29,777 --> 00:27:32,272
<i>Olive considered the
sheer number of crimes</i>

612
00:27:32,307 --> 00:27:35,352
<i>against delivery people and
how they were on the rise.</i>

613
00:27:44,876 --> 00:27:48,793
S.O.S.! O.S.! O.S.! S.O.S.!

614
00:27:48,856 --> 00:27:51,543
This pie smells delicious.

615
00:27:56,678 --> 00:28:00,762
Pies for breakfast always
remind me of mother.

616
00:28:01,055 --> 00:28:02,973
Vermouth always
reminds me of mother.

617
00:28:03,106 --> 00:28:04,602
Why are we having pie,

618
00:28:04,897 --> 00:28:06,990
- and who the hell are you?
- Forgive Lily.

619
00:28:07,027 --> 00:28:09,872
The last time we had visitors,
there was a home invasion.

620
00:28:10,066 --> 00:28:11,811
That was all over
the evening news.

621
00:28:12,107 --> 00:28:14,902
You're Darling Mermaid Darlings
Vivian and Lily Charles.

622
00:28:14,958 --> 00:28:17,501
I saw you perform at the
Callum County Country Fair

623
00:28:17,616 --> 00:28:19,193
when I was a little girl.

624
00:28:21,117 --> 00:28:23,492
Olive is in the pie industry.

625
00:28:23,827 --> 00:28:25,161
Really?

626
00:28:25,496 --> 00:28:27,541
Someone has made you
the happy recipients

627
00:28:27,667 --> 00:28:30,001
of a pie from the Pie Hole,
as in "shut your."

628
00:28:30,297 --> 00:28:32,941
Or, in this case,
"open your," 'cause it's real good.

629
00:28:33,428 --> 00:28:36,673
The Pie Hole-- I like it.
It's provocative.

630
00:28:37,095 --> 00:28:39,970
Well, you must love pie to
make it your life's work.

631
00:28:40,176 --> 00:28:41,631
Lots to love at the Pie Hole.

632
00:28:41,886 --> 00:28:43,650
There's gruyère
baked into the crust.

633
00:28:43,687 --> 00:28:46,440
- Oh, I didn't even know we did that.
- Charlotte loved gruyère.

634
00:28:46,475 --> 00:28:47,822
We recently lost our niece,

635
00:28:48,026 --> 00:28:51,060
- lonely tourist Charlotte Charles.
- It's all over the news.

636
00:28:51,236 --> 00:28:52,853
I am so sorry for your loss.

637
00:28:53,106 --> 00:28:54,580
I'm sure you're
sick of hearing it.

638
00:28:54,618 --> 00:28:56,560
I don't want to beat
a sentiment to d--

639
00:28:58,537 --> 00:29:00,991
I'm so sorry for your loss.

640
00:29:02,156 --> 00:29:04,032
This has to be from
that young man

641
00:29:04,048 --> 00:29:06,343
who lived next door when
Charlotte was a girl.

642
00:29:06,375 --> 00:29:08,412
Oh, he had a filthy
mind as a child.

643
00:29:08,707 --> 00:29:11,622
He gave Charlotte a beaver
t-shirt for her 8th birthday.

644
00:29:12,258 --> 00:29:14,581
- What did we call him?
- "Beaver boy."

645
00:29:14,798 --> 00:29:16,002
Beaver boy.

646
00:29:16,345 --> 00:29:18,311
Seems like he grew up
to be a nice young man.

647
00:29:18,347 --> 00:29:20,241
Beaver boy did say
he was a pie maker.

648
00:29:20,346 --> 00:29:22,242
I imagine he gives
lots of people pie.

649
00:29:22,387 --> 00:29:23,801
Beaver boy's a pie maker?

650
00:29:24,098 --> 00:29:26,391
Who was childhood
sweethearts with your niece,

651
00:29:26,557 --> 00:29:29,223
lonely tourist Charlotte Charles,
who is dead?

652
00:29:29,856 --> 00:29:31,182
Presently?

653
00:29:32,647 --> 00:29:35,353
<i>The truth about the dead
girl who wasn't dead</i>

654
00:29:35,457 --> 00:29:37,151
<i>vibrated on
Olive's tongue.</i>

655
00:29:37,187 --> 00:29:40,030
<i>She dare not let it out,
so she took another bite.</i>

656
00:29:42,826 --> 00:29:45,862
<i>Not realizing Louis Schatz
was dead and wedged</i>

657
00:29:45,877 --> 00:29:48,300
<i>between chilling dough
and yesterday's eggs,</i>

658
00:29:48,336 --> 00:29:51,371
<i>Emerson Cod prepared to
monitor every move he made,</i>

659
00:29:51,398 --> 00:29:53,583
<i>in hopes of finding
buried treasure.</i>

660
00:29:54,677 --> 00:29:57,753
- Hi, um, one of the Schatz brothers--
- It's Louis.

661
00:29:58,008 --> 00:30:00,242
Louis Schatz is in my freezer,
and I'm not sure how he got there,

662
00:30:00,277 --> 00:30:02,231
because it doesn't look
like it was his own doing,

663
00:30:02,266 --> 00:30:03,953
on account of he's
dead and all.

664
00:30:03,965 --> 00:30:05,663
- You being set up.
- He said we're being set up.

665
00:30:05,705 --> 00:30:07,450
Why would anyone
want to set us up?

666
00:30:07,477 --> 00:30:08,853
No, you being set up.

667
00:30:09,147 --> 00:30:11,322
- Why would anyone want to set me up?
- Hell if I know.

668
00:30:11,358 --> 00:30:13,283
Maybe they figure,
since you killed the other one...

669
00:30:13,318 --> 00:30:15,200
- Have I been exposed?
- Does somebody know?

670
00:30:15,238 --> 00:30:16,480
Somebody knows something,

671
00:30:16,655 --> 00:30:19,303
and that somebody probably
already called the police.

672
00:30:20,076 --> 00:30:22,733
Hey, the police are here.

673
00:30:34,966 --> 00:30:35,793
Hi.

674
00:30:35,807 --> 00:30:37,331
You need to follow us.

675
00:30:37,585 --> 00:30:39,223
- Where are we going?
- You're going to heaven.

676
00:30:39,256 --> 00:30:41,100
- I got in?
- Yeah, and heaven's closing

677
00:30:41,135 --> 00:30:42,852
- in like five minutes.
- Or one, actually.

678
00:30:42,896 --> 00:30:44,693
Heaven's closing in
like one minute.

679
00:30:57,698 --> 00:30:59,902
Hey, Emerson,
you going to heaven, too?

680
00:31:00,075 --> 00:31:02,333
- Yeah, we all going to heaven.
- That's so weird.

681
00:31:02,365 --> 00:31:04,660
- We died at the same time.
- Mm-hmm. The rapture.

682
00:31:04,697 --> 00:31:06,453
- No way.
- Yes way.

683
00:31:07,827 --> 00:31:09,532
- Is Larry here?
- Yeah,

684
00:31:09,616 --> 00:31:11,660
he told us to ask you what
you did with all that stuff

685
00:31:11,696 --> 00:31:13,412
you stole off those dead folks.

686
00:31:13,797 --> 00:31:15,802
Yeah, but first,
you got to tell us who killed you.

687
00:31:15,838 --> 00:31:18,223
- Heaven would want to know.
- I choked on a piece of tongue.

688
00:31:18,256 --> 00:31:19,923
Yours or somebody else's?

689
00:31:20,295 --> 00:31:23,300
<i>In this instance,
the tongue belonged to a cow.</i>

690
00:31:23,638 --> 00:31:26,520
<i>Although Louis Schatz had
been limiting his portions,</i>

691
00:31:26,556 --> 00:31:29,603
<i>they weren't so small they
couldn't block his windpipe</i>

692
00:31:29,845 --> 00:31:32,392
<i>when he was confronted
by an angry customer.</i>

693
00:31:35,937 --> 00:31:38,180
He said something about
a civil war heirloom.

694
00:31:38,277 --> 00:31:39,602
Then I lost consciousness.

695
00:31:39,986 --> 00:31:41,981
I usually cough it up
before I pass out.

696
00:31:42,276 --> 00:31:44,502
- 5 seconds.
- There's no seat belts in this car.

697
00:31:44,536 --> 00:31:45,791
Wait, wait, wait, wait!

698
00:31:45,807 --> 00:31:47,610
What did you do
with all that stuff

699
00:31:47,696 --> 00:31:49,811
you stole off
those dead... folk?

700
00:31:49,828 --> 00:31:51,283
